Plug-in name: Volatile
Plug-in shortname: volatile
Description:
support for volatile accesses and calls through function pointers

Most options of the form '-volatile-option-name' and without any parameter
have an opposite with the name '-volatile-no-option-name'.

Most options of the form '-option-name' and without any parameter
have an opposite with the name '-no-option-name'.

Options taking a string as argument should preferably be written
-option-name="argument".

***** LIST OF AVAILABLE OPTIONS:

-volatile           builds a new project (named "Volatile") where volatile
                    accesses are simulated by function calls (opposite option
                    is -no-volatile)
-volatile-basetype  use base-type for int, float and enums for the
                    instrumentation related to -volatile-binding option
                    (opposite option is -volatile-no-basetype)
-volatile-binding <f,...>  allows binding of volatile accesses to functions
                    <f,...> (preferably use -volatile-binding="f,...")
-volatile-binding-auto  allows automatic binding of volatiles accesses to
                    functions: <prefix>Rd_<typename> and
                    <prefix>Wr_<typename> (opposite option is
                    -volatile-no-binding-auto)
-volatile-binding-call-pointer  replaces calls through function pointers by
                    direct calls to functions:
                    <prefix>Call_<result-type>_<param-types> (opposite option
                    is -volatile-no-binding-call-pointer)
-volatile-binding-prefix <str>  adds <str> as prefix to function names for
                    automatic binding (preferably use
                    -volatile-binding-prefix="str")
-volatile-call-pointer <f,...>  stub call to pointer functions to the
                    provided functions (indexed by type) (preferably use
                    -volatile-call-pointer="f,...")
-volatile-fct <f,...>  Only process the given function(s) (preferably use
                    -volatile-fct="f,...")

*** DEBUG

-volatile-debug <n>  level of debug for plug-in Volatile (default to 0)

*** GETTING INFORMATION

-volatile-help      help of plug-in Volatile
-volatile-h         alias for option -volatile-help

*** OUTPUT MESSAGES

-volatile-log <K_1:file_1,...>  copy log messages from Volatile to a file.
                    <K> is a combination of these characters:
                    a: ALL messages (equivalent to 'dfiruw')
                    d: debug       e: user or internal error (same as 'iu')
                    f: feedback    i: internal error
                    r: result      u: user error    w: warning
                    An empty <K> (e.g. ":file.txt") defaults to 'iruw'. One
                    plug-in can output to several files and vice-versa.
                    (preferably use -volatile-log="K_1:file_1,...")
-volatile-msg-key <k1[,...,kn]>  enables message display for categories
                    <k1>,...,<kn>. Use -volatile-msg-key help to get a list
                    of available categories, and * to enable all categories
                    (preferably use -volatile-msg-key="k1[,...,kn]")
-volatile-verbose <n>  level of verbosity for plug-in Volatile (default to 1)
-volatile-warn-key <k1[=s1][,...,kn[=sn]]>  set warning status for category
                    <k1> to <s1>,...,<kn> to <sn>. Use -volatile-warn-key
                    help to get a list of available categories, and * to
                    enable all categories. Possible statuses are inactive,
                    feedback, warning, error, abort, feedback-once,
                    warning-once, error-once. Defaults to warning.
                    (preferably use
                    -volatile-warn-key="k1[=s1][,...,kn[=sn]]")
